Lawmakers troubled over anthrax mishap demand answers
----field----
field: {446A339B-E1D9-4DE1-8B5E-DB7942EF1723}
name: Body
key: body
content-length: 3034

<p>Bipartisan leaders from the House Energy and Commerce Committee on 28 May demanded answers from the heads of the Department of Defense (DOD) and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) about what led to live anthrax being shipped to numerous laboratories across the US and to an American military base in South Korea.</p><p>Representatives Fred Upton (Republican-Michigan), E&C chairman; Frank Pallone (Democrat-New Jersey), the committee's ranking member; Tim Murphy (Republican-Pennsylvania), chairman of the E&C Oversight and Investigations Subcommittee; and Diana DeGette (Democrat-Colorado), subcommittee ranking member, gave DOD Secretary Ash Carter and CDC Director Dr Thomas Frieden until 5 June to brief the lawmakers about what led to the mishap.</p><p>DOD and CDC <a href="http://www.scripintelligence.com/home/Live-anthrax-may-have-reached-numerous-US-labs-358624" target="_new">confirmed on 27 May</a> that researchers working at the US Army's Dugway Proving Grounds in Utah accidentally shipped live <i>Bacillus anthracis</i> to at least 18 private, academic and federal labs in nine states and to Osan Air Base in Korea.</p><p>It's currently unclear what may have gone wrong with the irradiation process at the US Army lab.</p><p>While no lab workers have developed anthrax symptoms, at least four lab workers in Delaware, Texas and Wisconsin have started on post-exposure prophylaxis antibiotic therapy, a CDC spokesman told <i>Scrip</i>.</p><p>Osan Air Base also said that at least 22 of its personnel may have been exposed and as a precautionary measure, all personnel were provided with examinations, antibiotics and in some instances, vaccinations.</p><p>The E&C Oversight and Investigations Subcommittee already is investigating other near-calamitous government lab mishaps involving <a href="http://www.scripintelligence.com/home/CDC-anthrax-mishap-puts-spotlight-on-biosafety-lab-vulnerabilities-352431" target="_new">anthrax</a>, the <a href="http://www.scripintelligence.com/home/Anthrax-smallpox-and-H5N1-Bad-beyond-Walter-White-352849" target="_new">H5N1</a> influenza virus, <a href="http://www.scripintelligence.com/home/CDC-reports-another-lab-mishap-this-time-Ebola-355849" target="_new">Ebola</a>, <a href="http://www.scripintelligence.com/home/Smallpox-discovery-triggers-FBI-probe-NIH-lab-search-352714" target="_new">smallpox</a> and <a href="http://www.scripintelligence.com/home/Ricin-other-unsecured-pathogens-found-at-NIH-FDA-353742" target="_new">other agents</a>.</p><p>"We are troubled" by the latest anthrax mishap, the lawmakers said in letters to Secretary Carter and Dr Frieden. </p><p>Senator Bill Nelson (Democrat-Florida) also demanded an explanation from the US Army about the activities that required the use of research on anthrax samples. </p><p>He also called for Army Secretary John McHugh to explain what precautions were taken to ensure the public and personnel were being kept safe when the military conducts such experiments.</p><p><p><p><p><p><p><p><p><p><p>
